Looking at the mutation, the change is in the `gettype` function:

- Original: `} else if (part_count_diff == -1) {` (only executes when link has one fewer path part than page)
- Mutated: `} else if (true) {` (always executes this branch when `part_count_diff == 1`)

The affected branch handles `part_count_diff == 1` (link has one more path part than page). In the original code, after the `part_count_diff == 1` block, there's a `} else if (part_count_diff == -1)` block. The mutation changes this to `} else if (true)`, which means the `-1` case now also runs when `part_count_diff == 1`.

Let me trace through the logic:
- When `part_count_diff == 1`: original falls through to `return "internal"`, mutated executes the `-1` block which checks `if (pageurl_path.includes(linkurl_path)) return "uplevel"`
- When `part_count_diff == -1`: original checks `if (pageurl_path.includes(linkurl_path)) return "uplevel"`, mutated also executes this (same behavior)

Wait, let me re-read. The `<PLACEHOLDER>` is the content of the `part_count_diff == 1` block. The original value is `} else if (part_count_diff == -1) {` which means the `part_count_diff == 1` block is empty, and then there's a `-1` check. The mutated value is `} else if (true) {` which means the `-1` check always runs after the `part_count_diff == 1` empty block.

So when `part_count_diff == 1`, the mutated code also checks `if (pageurl_path.includes(linkurl_path)) return "uplevel"`. This would incorrectly return "uplevel" instead of "internal" when the link has one more path segment and the page path includes the link path.

Let me construct a test case where `part_count_diff == 1` and `pageurl_path.includes(linkurl_path)` is true, which would return "uplevel" in mutated but "internal" in original.

Example: link = `http://example.com/aaa/`, page = `http://example.com/aaa/bbb/`
- linkurl_parts = ["aaa"], pageurl_parts = ["aaa", "bbb"]
- part_count_diff = 1 - 2 = -1... that's the wrong direction.

