- linkurl_parts = ["aaa", "bbb"], pageurl_parts = ["aaa"]
- part_count_diff = 2 - 1 = 1
- pageurl_path = "/aaa/", linkurl_path = "/aaa/bbb/"
- pageurl_path.includes(linkurl_path) = "/aaa/".includes("/aaa/bbb/") = false

Try: link = `http://example.com/aaa/`, page = `http://example.com/`
- linkurl_parts = ["aaa"], pageurl_parts = []
- part_count_diff = 1 - 0 = 1
- pageurl_path = "/", linkurl_path = "/aaa/"
- pageurl_path.includes(linkurl_path) = "/".includes("/aaa/") = false

Hmm, it seems hard to make `pageurl_path.includes(linkurl_path)` true when `part_count_diff == 1`. The link has more parts, so link path is longer. Let me think again...

Actually wait - the mutation makes the `else if (true)` replace what was `else if (part_count_diff == -1)`. So when `part_count_diff == -1`, the behavior is the same. The difference is when `part_count_diff == 1`, the mutated code ALSO enters the `-1` block. But `pageurl_path.includes(linkurl_path)` when link has more parts would generally be false. So the mutation might not change behavior in most cases... unless there's a case where it does.

Let me reconsider - maybe the mutation causes `return "internal"` to be skipped when `part_count_diff == 1` and the condition is false, falling through differently. Actually the structure is the same - it still falls to `return "internal"`.

The key difference must be when `part_count_diff == 1` AND `pageurl_path.includes(linkurl_path)` is true. This seems geometrically impossible since link has more parts...

Actually, maybe I need to test the `-1` case to ensure it still works correctly in the mutated version. The mutation might break the `-1` case by making it unreachable... No, `else if (true)` would catch everything after `part_count_diff == 0`.

