Mutated `<PLACEHOLDER>`: `} else if (true) {`

So mutated:
```
if (part_count_diff == 0) { return "samelevel" }
else if (part_count_diff == 1) {
    // EMPTY
} else if (true) {
    if (pageurl_path.includes(linkurl_path)) return "uplevel";
}
```

So in the mutated version, when `part_count_diff == -1`, it still enters the `else if (true)` block. But also when `part_count_diff` is anything other than 0 or 1, it enters that block too.

The key difference: when `part_count_diff == 1`, original skips to `return "internal"`, but mutated... wait no. When `part_count_diff == 1`, it enters the first `else if` block (which is empty), then falls through to `return "internal"`. Same in both.

The real difference: when `part_count_diff == -1`, original enters `else if (part_count_diff == -1)`. Mutated also enters `else if (true)`. Same behavior.

When `part_count_diff` is something else (like -2, 2, etc.): original skips both else-ifs, returns "internal". Mutated enters `else if (true)`, checks `pageurl_path.includes(linkurl_path)`.

But wait - when `part_count_diff == 1` in mutated, it enters the FIRST else-if (empty block), so it does NOT enter the `else if (true)` block. So `part_count_diff == 1` behaves the same.

